mechanisms alive.

00:44:11.660 --> 00:44:14.300
But are there any
speculations about mechanisms

00:44:14.300 --> 00:44:15.560
that go directly to the DNA?

00:44:15.560 --> 00:44:18.370
Or is that DNA damaged
from the radiation just a

00:44:18.370 --> 00:44:21.224
given and has to be dealt with?

00:44:21.224 --> 00:44:22.640
IVAN PAULINO-LIMA:
So the question

00:44:22.640 --> 00:44:26.660
is about the radiation
effects on the DNA.

00:44:26.660 --> 00:44:30.530
So gamma rays, I think the
most severe type of damage

00:44:30.530 --> 00:44:32.644
on the DNA caused by
high-energy radiation

00:44:32.644 --> 00:44:34.310
like gamma rays is
double-strand breaks,

00:44:34.310 --> 00:44:38.010
but it also generates
a lot of free radicals

00:44:38.010 --> 00:44:42.490
and oxidative
stress in the cells.

00:44:42.490 --> 00:44:46.020
But I think what determines
the survival or cell

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:50.150
death is the accumulation
of this type of damage.

00:44:50.150 --> 00:44:54.190
Even Deinococcus will die if
the dose is high enough, because

00:44:54.190 --> 00:44:58.600
of this type of damage that
is not trivial to repair.

00:44:58.600 --> 00:45:02.230
It involves a
protein called RecA

00:45:02.230 --> 00:45:05.470
to recruit a whole
machinery of other enzymes

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:07.690
to repair this damage.

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:10.230
But it's very interesting
to know that Deinococcus

00:45:10.230 --> 00:45:12.650
does that within four hours.

00:45:12.650 --> 00:45:16.880
The genome can be
broken up to 200 pieces.

00:45:16.880 --> 00:45:19.160
And it will re-assemble
these pieces

00:45:19.160 --> 00:45:22.410
in the right position in the
right sequence within four

00:45:22.410 --> 00:45:23.100
hours.

00:45:23.100 --> 00:45:25.800
So it's very amazing
how efficient

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:29.720
is the DNA repair mechanism
from Deinococcus radiodurans.

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:33.370
AUDIENCE: So as a general rule,
if you have higher radiation

00:45:33.370 --> 00:45:36.770
rates in particular, does that
cause higher mutation rates,

00:45:36.770 --> 00:45:40.860
which then makes organisms
more easily evolve

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:43.784
to radiation resistance?

00:45:43.784 --> 00:45:45.700
IVAN PAULINO-LIMA: It
depends on the organism.

00:45:45.700 --> 00:45:47.740
In the case of
Deinococcus radiodurans,

00:45:47.740 --> 00:45:51.060
since they are very efficient
at repairing DNA damages,

00:45:51.060 --> 00:45:54.084
it's hard to get mutants for
Deinococcus radiodurans, which

00:45:54.084 --> 00:45:55.500
doesn't mean that
it's impossible.

00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:59.440
Actually, there are ways of
getting mutants of Deinococcus.

00:45:59.440 --> 00:46:02.990
But other organisms that are
less efficient at doing repair

00:46:02.990 --> 00:46:08.010
would be easier to get
mutants from radiation.

00:46:08.010 --> 00:46:14.400
That's what has been used I
think in 30, 40 years ago.

00:46:14.400 --> 00:46:17.945
That was the main method to
generate mutants, just boost

00:46:17.945 --> 00:46:19.220
an organism though radiation.

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:21.360
And then select whatever grows.

00:46:21.360 --> 00:46:23.070
And you would isolate mutants.

00:46:23.070 --> 00:46:28.320
I did it myself for my
undergraduate research.

00:46:28.320 --> 00:46:30.300
So I generated a lot
of mutants in the fungi

00:46:30.300 --> 00:46:33.990
that I was studying there.

00:46:33.990 --> 00:46:36.310
AUDIENCE: We have
seen a lot of progress

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:38.820
in space exploration
mainly in rocket

00:46:38.820 --> 00:46:44.870
and recently a lot of private
initiative, mainly SpaceX.

00:46:44.870 --> 00:46:46.960
Is this type of
research a blocker

00:46:46.960 --> 00:46:50.920
for getting into Mars
safely, because you

00:46:50.920 --> 00:46:53.270
seem like the extreme
radiation will

00:46:53.270 --> 00:46:55.750
be exposed for a long time?

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:58.260
Are we waiting for
this type of work

00:46:58.260 --> 00:47:01.090
in order to launch
the next rocket?

00:47:01.090 --> 00:47:03.080
IVAN PAULINO-LIMA:
No, actually not.

00:47:03.080 --> 00:47:07.840
I think people-- this
private initiatives are

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:13.190
contributing actually to develop
the field of space exploration.

00:47:13.190 --> 00:47:16.120
I think with current technology
with good current knowledge

00:47:16.120 --> 00:47:19.160
about radiation resistance,
we will eventually

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:22.790
go to Mars accepting the risks.

00:47:22.790 --> 00:47:25.460
But it would be nice to
come up with strategies

00:47:25.460 --> 00:47:28.330
to improve radiation
resistance of astronauts

00:47:28.330 --> 00:47:32.680
by using synthetic biology,
genetic engineering, and so on.

00:47:32.680 --> 00:47:35.050
But it by no means is stopping.

00:47:35.050 --> 00:47:36.940
I think it will
happen definitely even

00:47:36.940 --> 00:47:39.550
with current technology
and knowledge.

00:47:39.550 --> 00:47:42.120
And this is one
of the reasons why

00:47:42.120 --> 00:47:46.260
I believe that the
human mission to Mars

00:47:46.260 --> 00:47:48.310
will happen within
our generation.

00:47:48.310 --> 00:47:50.800
I think we will be able to
see that, one more reason

00:47:50.800 --> 00:47:56.340
to be thankful to live
in this exciting moment.

00:47:56.340 --> 00:47:57.480
I'm not that old.

00:47:57.480 --> 00:47:59.850
But I hear this story
about sending humans

00:47:59.850 --> 00:48:01.090
to Mars for a long time.

00:48:01.090 --> 00:48:04.910
But now, I believe that many
things are being put together.

00:48:04.910 --> 00:48:07.200
Technology is far faster.

00:48:07.200 --> 00:48:08.750
Rockets are being developed.

00:48:08.750 --> 00:48:11.990
All of this synthetic biology
revolution is happening.

00:48:11.990 --> 00:48:16.420
So I really believe now that
within the next two or three

00:48:16.420 --> 00:48:19.040
decades we will see the
first humans on Mars.

00:48:19.040 --> 00:48:22.060
And I hope there will not be
people saying that humans never

00:48:22.060 --> 00:48:23.340
went to Mars.

00:48:23.340 --> 00:48:24.590
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:48:24.590 --> 00:48:25.610
IVAN PAULINO-LIMA:
OK, thank you.

00:48:25.610 --> 00:48:26.610
Thank you very much.

00:48:26.610 --> 00:48:29.060
[APPLAUSE]

